-- Regression: REG-02 crash-canary for IRON_HIR_STMT_IF with elif/else branches.
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 37-02 introduced hir_to_lir.c's
-- collect_mono_enums_node AST walker, which declared a locally-shadowed
-- Iron_If struct guess that omitted elif_conds[] / elif_bodies[] /
-- elif_count between `body` and `else_body`. The walker crashed
-- deterministically on Linux x86_64 Release for any program containing
-- an if/elif/else chain, but macOS arm64 masked the bug for months
-- because the garbage bytes landed on the switch default case. Phase 66
-- added a _Static_assert on the real Iron_IfStmt layout and enabled
-- -Werror=switch-enum globally; this canary is the runtime regression
-- net so any future walker regression for IRON_NODE_IF surfaces
-- immediately in both Debug and Release CI.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** Iron_IfStmt carries
--   { span, kind, condition, body, elif_conds[], elif_bodies[],
--     elif_count, else_body }
-- Any walker case that fails to recurse into elif_conds[] or
-- elif_bodies[] silently drops sub-expressions from the lowered LIR --
-- exactly the defect class this canary protects against.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** Phase 67-08 added this fixture as a REG-02 crash
-- canary. Complements the existing hir_to_lir_elif_mono_walker.iron
-- (Phase 59 P01 reference fixture) -- that one is the original bug
-- reproduction, this is the REG-02 catalogue entry with distinct input
-- values for grep independence. CI integration: runs in both Debug and
-- Release via Phase 66-04's build-and-test-release job plus the
-- existing Debug integration job.
--
-- **Severity.** H (regression potential) -- the Phase 37-02 SIGSEGV was
-- a deterministic Linux x86_64 Release crash that hid for months
-- because no per-node-kind canary existed. This canary IS the missing
-- regression net.

func bucket(n: Int) -> Int {
  if n < -10 {
    return 0
  } elif n < 0 {
    return 1
  } elif n == 0 {
    return 2
  } elif n < 10 {
    return 3
  } elif n < 100 {
    return 4
  } else {
    return 5
  }
}

func main() {
  var total = 0
  total = total + bucket(-20)   -- 0
  total = total + bucket(-15)   -- 0
  total = total + bucket(-5)    -- 1
  total = total + bucket(0)     -- 2
  total = total + bucket(5)     -- 3
  total = total + bucket(50)    -- 4
  total = total + bucket(500)   -- 5
  println("total: {total}")
}
